# Git & Repository Integration

## 1. Remote Configuration
- **Target Repository:** `https://github.com/auzaniridzwan-oss`
- **Origin:** Ensure the remote origin is set to this GitHub profile.
- **Privacy:** Always maintain a robust `.gitignore` to prevent committing `node_modules`, `.env` files, or LocalStorage dumps.

## 2. Commit Convention (Conventional Commits)
All commits must follow the `type(scope): description` format to ensure a clean history:
- `feat`: A new feature (e.g., `feat(ui): add passenger details step`).
- `fix`: A bug fix (e.g., `fix(braze): resolve init timeout`).
- `docs`: Documentation only changes.
- `style`: Changes that do not affect the meaning of the code (formatting, missing semi-colons, etc).
- `refactor`: A code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature.
- `chore`: Updating build tasks, package manager configs, etc.

## 3. Branching Strategy
- **Main Branch:** `main` (Production-ready code).
- **Feature Branches:** `feature/feature-name` (e.g., `feature/braze-sdk-setup`).
- **Fix Branches:** `fix/issue-name`.

## 4. GitHub Actions & CI
- **Vercel Integration:** Ensure the repository is linked to the [auzani-ridzwans-projects](https://vercel.com/auzani-ridzwans-projects) Vercel account for automatic deployments on push.
- **Workflow:** If creating a `.github/workflows/main.yml`, ensure it includes a step for linting JS and CSS to maintain the standards defined in the other `.mdc` rules.